Introduction

Missing data is a common concern, especially in the health care sector where datasets like Electronic Health Records (EHR) are sometimes incomplete for a variety of reasons, includes technological issues, in applicability, or information loss. If missing data is not appropriately considered, it might result in biased results, reduced reliability, and compromising conclusions in clinical epidemiology and other healthcare research (Salgado et al. 2016). Results can be affected by missing values, which is the most common problem for statistical models that depend on complete datasets. Either imputation or elimination can be used to address missing data in order to eleminate these problems. Imputation is the recommended method since it lowers the possibility of loss of data and protects the integrity of the dataset (Pedersen et al. 2017).

Missing completely at random (MCAR) and missing not at random (MNAR) are two examples of the underlying mechanisms of missingness that heavily influence the choice of imputation technique. Imputation techniques range from simple techniques like mean substitution to more complex strategies like multiple imputation, which guesses missing values by generating multiple data sets and merging the resulting results to take uncertainty into account (Pedersen et al. 2017). The ability of these highly sophisticated methods, primarily multiple imputation, to minimize bias and maintain the accuracy of investigations has made them popular in clinical research (Salgado et al. 2016). The purpose of this project is to investigate and contrast different imputation methods, examining how well they handle diverse situations involving missing data and maintaining the validity of datasets in clinical epidemiology and healthcare research.

The common non-parametric regression model is \(Y_i = m(X_i) + \varepsilon_i\), where \(Y_i\) can be defined as the sum of the regression function value \(m(x)\) for \(X_i\). Here \(m(x)\) is unknown and \(\varepsilon_i\) some errors. With the help of this definition, we can create the estimation for local averaging i.e. \(m(x)\) can be estimated with the product of \(Y_i\) average and \(X_i\) is near to \(x\). In other words, this means that we are discovering the line through the data points with the help of surrounding data points. The estimation formula is printed below (R Core Team 2019):

\[ M_n(x) = \sum_{i=1}^{n} W_n (X_i) Y_i \tag{1} \]\(W_n(x)\) is the sum of weights that belongs to all real numbers. Weights are positive numbers and small if \(X_i\) is far from \(x\).

Another equation:

\[ y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 +\varepsilon_i \]

ggplot1 = murders %>% ggplot(mapping = aes(x=population/10^6, y=total)) 

  ggplot1 + geom_point(aes(col=region), size = 4) +
  geom_text_repel(aes(label=abb)) +
  scale_x_log10() +
  scale_y_log10() +
  geom_smooth(formula = "y~x", method=lm,se = F)+
  xlab("Populations in millions (log10 scale)") + 
  ylab("Total number of murders (log10 scale)") +
  ggtitle("US Gun Murders in 2010") +
  scale_color_discrete(name = "Region")+
